<br>
HL2 has great modding potential planned anyway, which will likely be very extensively documented. Valve wants mods, and good, free ones. Mods like Counter-Strike, that keep the game selling for years. Personally I never got into CS, but I played Action Quake, which was the previous project by the CS creators. It kept Quake 2 on my hard drive for longer than it deserved alone...<br>
<br>
Basically, I doubt very much that they fear mods. From what I had read, they have already given people the toolkit to start on them, which is all they need. Mods are not programmed using the source code. Maybe if someone wanted to rip off the engine, but usually engine licensing fees are so small as to make that a waste. It'd cost less to license it (from the outset, not royalties) than to hire one programmer for a year to adapt it (if it's similar to the what, $40k that id charges?).<br>
<br>
